sentences: Max Graham (; born April 17, 1971) is a British-Canadian DJ, composer, and producer of dance music.

Known for fusing progressive house, trance, and techno, he is most famous for his open-to-close DJ Sets (where he typically plays 6 to 8 hours),  his Cycles CD series/radio show, and his remix of the classic song "Owner of a Lonely Heart" (by Yes) in 2005.
Graham was born in London, England, and lived in Spain, New York City and Los Angeles before settling in Ottawa, Canada, in 1989.
At age 15, in 1986, he began as a hip-hop DJ before discovering dance music in the 1990s.
At age 15, in 1986, he began as a hip-hop DJ before discovering dance music in the 1990s.
He was a resident DJ at the famed Atomic Nightclub in Ottawa from 1997–2001.
He has been touring globally as a DJ and producing melodic dance music since 2000.
1997–2001: Atomic Nightclub, Hope Recordings =

During his residency at Atomic Nightclub, Graham was discovered by label executives and signed to Hope Recordings; one of his first productions, “Airtight”, was noticed by Nick Warren and Paul Oakenfold in 2000.
He gained immediate acclaim and was voted #23 in the DJMag top 100 DJs for 2001 and was chosen to mix the famous Tranceport CD Series (Tranceport 4) that year.
2002–04: ShineMusic and the "sidechain" mixes ===
Graham created the "Shine" concept in 2002, which included a mix CD, a label (Shinemusic), and club nights.
In 2004, Graham signed two singles to Sander Kleinenberg's Little Mountain label, entitled "Does She Know Yet?"

== Career == | === 2015–17: Leaving Armada, moving away from trance, changing sound ===

sentences: In 2015, Graham began to move away from trance (due to the changing sound that no longer appealed to him) and left Armada, closing down his Rebrand label in the process.
section: == Career == | === 2015–17: Leaving Armada, moving away from trance, changing sound ===

sentences: In late 2017, Graham announced via Facebook that he was ending the weekly Cycles Radio episodes and taking an extended break from touring and making music.

In 2019, Graham returned to the scene and announced via social media in August that he was in the studio working on his second artist album as well as relaunching Cycles Radio with a new monthly format.
In March 2021, however, Graham announced that he would be taking another indefinite hiatus.
Graham is known mostly these days as a DJ for his open-to-close sets, where he typically plays 6–8 hours.

Known for fusing progressive house, trance, and techno, he is most famous for his open-to-close DJ Sets (where he typically plays 6 to 8 hours),  his Cycles CD series/radio show, and his remix of the classic song "Owner of a Lonely Heart" (by Yes) in 2005.
He was a resident DJ at the famed Atomic Nightclub in Ottawa from 1997–2001.
1997–2001: Atomic Nightclub, Hope Recordings =

During his residency at Atomic Nightclub, Graham was discovered by label executives and signed to Hope Recordings; one of his first productions, “Airtight”, was noticed by Nick Warren and Paul Oakenfold in 2000.
Tiesto also put “Airtight” on his In Search of Sunrise 2 album.
That same year, “Airtight” was nominated for a Juno Award.
He gained immediate acclaim and was voted #23 in the DJMag top 100 DJs for 2001 and was chosen to mix the famous Tranceport CD Series (Tranceport 4) that year.
Graham created the "Shine" concept in 2002, which included a mix CD, a label (Shinemusic), and club nights.
From 2008 to 2017, Graham released a new Cycles CD almost every year as a self-proclaimed “snapshot” of his current DJ sound.

Graham is known mostly these days as a DJ for his open-to-close sets, where he typically plays 6–8 hours.

He has toured to over 75 countries and performed at such festivals as Ultra, Tomorrowland and Dance Valley as well as performed at some of the most famed venues in the world, including Pacha, Ibiza; Ushuaia, Ibiza; Twilo, New York; Space Terrace, Miami; and open-to-close sets at Cielo, New York, and Output, New York.
